XCVI. ΟΝ EARL OF PEMBROKE’S DEATH.

The event here lamented took place in 1630. See Vol. 1. No. XXXIV.

ARGUMENT.

What avails golden virtue, or honours, birth, troops of friends, royal favour, wealth? Among England’s sons Fortune’s greatest favourite, iore· most oi the peerage, thou, Pembroke, perishest. Since thy master’s¹ dark demise, no day has dawned so dark beneath the pole.

¹ The king, James 1. os Engiand, VI. os Scotlond, died in 1625.

XCVI. IN OBITUM COMITIS PEMBROCHII.

Aurea quid virtus, quid prosunt sanguin, honores, Mille clientelae, gratia regis, opes?

Angligenas inter fortunatissime nuper, Pembrochi, et procerum gloria prima, cadis.
